response:
 Here is a pattern you could notice. First, notice that 2 is not in the set so we can assume all elements are odd. Now, notice that odd integers must be i. e. $\pm p_2$ for an odd prime $p_2$, since all primes are odd. For instance, $23=11+12$. Now, though, notice that 11 is in the set so each element is $\pm 11$. But we can show that one of $\pm 11$ isn't in the set. Notice that 11 is an even number away from all other primes congruent to 10 (mod 12) (since primes congruent to 3 mod 12) since they all leave a remainder of 1 on division by 3 but 11 leaves a remainder of 2. This means all primes except those that are congruent to 10 mod 12 have 11 as a difference. However, you can note that all odd primes greater than 3 can be written as 6k+1 or 6k-1. For those of the form 6k-1, their difference with 11 will be even and not odd, so the only primes that aren't at least the difference of 11 are those congruent to 10 (mod 12). However, since we have excluded those, then in fact they are all the odd numbers not being the sum of primes. This completes our question. We have proven the hint and solved the follow up ones. $\square$
