The State of North Carolina will need over one trillion dollars if it has a population of 6 in 3.5 seconds. How can the population of North Carolina be expressed in standard notation?
Given Data:

Time taken to have a population of 6 in North Carolina is {eq}t = 3.5\;{\rm{s}}

{/eq}.
Number of people in North Carolina is {eq}p = 1\;{\rm{trillion}} = 1 \times {10^{12}}

{/eq}.


A trillion is a large number. The value of trillion is {eq}1 \times {10^{12}}

{/eq}.



Cross multiply both the sides to find the population of the North Carolina required to have a population of 6.

{eq}\begin{align*}

\left( {\dfrac{t}{p}} \right) \times 1 \times {10^{12}} &= 6\\

\left( {\dfrac{{3.5\;{\rm{s}}}}{{1 \times {{10}^{12}}}}} \right) \times 1 \times {10^{12}} &= 6\\

3.5\;{\rm{s}} \times 6\;{\rm{trillion}} &= 6\\

&= 21\;{\rm{s}}\\

&= 2.1 \times {10^{13}}\;{\rm{s}}

\end{align*}

{/eq}



Hence, the population of the North Carolina required is {eq}2.1 \times {10^{13}}\;{\rm{s}}.

{/eq}



Therefore, the population of North Carolina can be expressed in standard notation as {eq}2.1 \times {10^{13}}\;{\rm{s}}.

